1. Plain Logit

Estimation Procedure

  • The indirect utility function, assuming no heterogeneity, is given by \[ u_{ijm} = \bar{\beta}_0 + x_{j} \bar{\beta}_1 + \xi_{jm} + \varepsilon_{ijm}. \]
  • Define the mean utility: \[ \delta_j = \bar{\beta}_0 + x_{j}' \bar{\beta}_1 + \xi_{jm} \]
    • Then, \(u_{ijm} = \delta_{j} + \varepsilon_{ijm}\).
  • As we have seen in the class, the market share (or, choice probability) is given by \[ s_{jm}(\delta) = \frac{\exp(\delta_{jm})}{1 + \sum_{k=1}^J\exp(\delta_{km})} \]
    • \(\delta_0\) is normalized to \(0\).
  • By Berry inversion, we have \[ \log(s_{0m}) - \log(s_{jm}) = \delta_{jm} \]

Estimation

  • Compute share and \(\delta\).
mkt_size = 100000    # market size is 100,000 by assumption

df_market <- df_market %>% 
  bind_rows(outside) %>% 
  arrange(market, product) %>% 
  group_by(market) %>% 
  mutate(total_inside = sum(quantity, na.rm = TRUE)) %>% 
  mutate(quantity = if_else(product == 0, mkt_size - total_inside , quantity)) %>% 
  mutate(share = quantity / mkt_size) %>%
  mutate(delta_plain = log(share / share[1])) %>% 
  ungroup()

df_market

reg_result <- lm(delta_plain ~ characteristics, data = df_market, subset = (product != 0))

2. BLP approach

Estimation Procedure

  • The indirect utility function is \[\begin{align} u_{ijm} & =\left(\bar{\beta}_{0}+\beta_{0}^{u}\nu_{i0m}\right)+x_{j}\cdot\left(\bar{\beta}_{1}+\beta_{1}^{u}\nu_{i1m}\right)+\xi_{jm}+\varepsilon_{ijm}\\ & =\left(\bar{\beta}_{0}+x_{j}\bar{\beta}_{1}+\xi_{jm}\right)+\left(\beta_{0}^{u}\nu_{i0m}+x_{j}\beta_{1}^{u}\nu_{i1m}\right)+\varepsilon_{ijm}\\ & =\delta_{jm}+\mu_{ijm}+\varepsilon_{ijm}. \end{align}\]

  • First, we simulate consumer-level heterogeneity, \(\nu_{vkm}\).

  • Let \(\theta = (\beta_0^u, \beta_1^u)\).

  • Using the simulated data and some initial \(\delta_{jm}\), we compute the simulated share by: \[ \hat{s}_{jm}(\delta, \theta)=\frac{1}{ns}\sum_{i=1}^{ns}\left[\frac{\exp(\delta_{jm}+\mu_{ijm}(\theta))}{1+\sum_{j'=1}^{10}\exp(\delta_{j'm}+\mu_{ij'm}(\theta))}\right] \]

    • By contraction mapping, we can obtain \(\delta_{jm}^*(\theta)\).

  • With \(\delta_{jm}^*\) at hand, we estimate fixed effect FE model to obtain \(\alpha_j^*\) and \(\xi_{jm}^*(\theta)\):

\[\begin{align*} \delta_{jm}^{*}(\theta) & =\left(\bar{\beta}_{0}+x_{j}\bar{\beta}_{1}\right)+\xi_{jm}\\ & =\alpha_{j}+\xi_{jm} \end{align*}\]

  • Once we obtain \(\alpha_j^*\) we can estimate \((\bar{\beta}_0,\bar{\beta}_1)\) by the following regression: \[ \alpha_j^*(\theta) = \bar{\beta}_{0}+x_{j}\bar{\beta}_{1} + \text{error.} \]

  • Notice that the above procedure solely depends on \(\theta\).

    • Namely, if we provide the value of \(\theta\), then we get all the folloing parameters, which depends on \(\theta\):
      • \(\delta, \alpha, \xi, \bar{\beta}_{0}, \bar{\beta}_{1}\)
    • Since economic theory (or assumption) suggests that there is no endogeneity, a natural way to estimate \(\theta\) is minimizing the squared sums of \(\xi_{jm}(\theta)\).

  • Minimize the objective function \(\xi^{\ast \top}\xi^*\).

Estimation

  • Parameters we want to estimate: \(\theta = (\beta_0^u, \beta_1^u)\).
    • As descrived above, \((\bar{\beta}_0,\bar{\beta}_1)\) is automatically estimated if \(\theta\) is given.
theta = c(-1, 2)

  • In sum, we get the following estimation result by plain logit and BLP:

\[ \begin{align*} \text{plain logit}:\qquad & u_{ijm}=-3.34+1.00x_{j}+\xi_{jm}+\varepsilon_{ijm}\\ \text{BLP}:\qquad & u_{ijm}=\left(-2.04+-2.11\nu_{i0m}\right)+x_{j}\cdot\left(-1.33+0.261\nu_{i1m}\right)+\xi_{jm}+\varepsilon_{ijm} \end{align*} \]
